<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Memorandum for the Liaison Committee from the Science and Technology Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> from the Science and Technology Committee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (SCE0026)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This memorandum sets out some of the ways in which the Committee has sought to improve its functions since the Liaison Committee began inquiring into Committee effectiveness.  A number of changes in the way the Committee has approached its work have evolved from both an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">awayday</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and from the recommendations of  the Liaison Committee report. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Committee Away day</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee, as part of its Valley of Death inquiry, visited the Warwick Manufacturing Group facility in Coventry.  They were offered the opportunity to use a boardroom there as a base for considering the work of the Committee and how it could operate more effectively.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On 16 July 2012 the Committee accepted the recommendations of the Members who attended the away day.  These recommendations have been reproduced as Appendix 1 to this paper.  A number of these have been progressed while others have not.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Liaison Committee report</span></p><p style="font-size:20pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">The Liaison Committee, on 8 November 2012, published its </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmliaisn/697/69702.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline; text-transform:none">report</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none"> into select committee effectiveness.  The report contained a number of recommendations for Committees that may contribute to improving effectiveness.  These recommendations are reproduced in the Appendix. They include comments on how committees arrange their work programme, changes to reports, and training for committee members.  The Science and Technology Committee, in January this year, considered how it wished to incorporate these suggestions into its work:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 24.26pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s the Committee operating in line with the Liaison Committee’s suggestions for best practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">? (3)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 24.26pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s there anything from the recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that needed to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the Committee’s work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">? (4-10)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 24.26pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommittee members </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would like training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">? (16)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee had a brief discussion on these issues and decided that they were content with the current working practice of the Committee.  They had no strong feelings on the recommended formatting and that they were content to follow the recommendations for conclusions and recommendations in reports. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Changes to Committee practice arising from the away day</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has expanded its outputs during its work to ensure that it has a greater engagement with the public.  There has been a greater utilisation of letters to Ministers (such as following the one-off session on Digital by default), greater use of twitter to report on committee activity and exploratory work on the potential for small highlight documents for the Members’ Library at the end of a report.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has more regularly scheduled extended time, usually on a Monday, for private business considerations such as report considerations.  The move to electronic circulation (with supplementary paper from the Vote Office where necessary) would seem to have addressed the issue of papers being received in a timely fashion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt; text-transform:uppercase"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has scheduled additional time to discuss reports at the end of the inquiry to inform the drafting of the report.  Additional time was provided during the Climate inquiry to discuss progress and current thoughts prior to the final evidence session. Reports have, by default, been scheduled two weekends for consideration rather than one.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee staff have experimented with ways in which the Committee might examine and consider a report.  The Educating Engineers report was amended live on a large screen during consideration, draft reports have been sent to the Chair electronically and the format of the amendment documents have been subject to some experimentation, including providing original and amended blocks of text to provide context to the amendments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has invited some nervous witnesses into the Committee room, just before the public session, to introduce them to the surroundings and to the Members in private.  This was especially important for some apprentices giving evidence in the Educating Engineers inquiry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has commissioned work from the National Audit Office to provide a means to stimulate discussion within the STEM community on government spending in R&amp;D. A number of suggested inquiries were submitted to the Committee on the back of that and the current horizon scanning inquiry resulted from it.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee staff have worked with the Media Officer, at the start of the Climate, Clinical Trials and Women in STEM careers inquiries, to identify the best way to pitch the enquiry to media, identify potential points to engage the media and enhance the coverage of the inquiry come its conclusion and publication of its report.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee website has received a makeover that ensures that it is more engaging.  The Committee staff are working with the House Web and Intranet Service to ensure that the pages are increasingly interesting to look at, up to date and interactive.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Changes to Committee practice relating to the Liaison Committee report</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.45pt; padding-left:7.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has taken the opportunity during its business to frequently consider its future business.  It has not yet followed up on its initial away day.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 26.03pt; padding-left:2.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has discussed different ways to approach questions but has not yet found a method that it prefers over the usual practice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 26.03pt; padding-left:2.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has been more pro-active in following up on its inquiries.  It has followed up its report on the Forensic Science Service with another inquiry a year later, the Marine science inquiry with a one-off session to check on progress and aspects of the Cybercrime inquiry with a one-off session on the Government Digital by Default policy.  The Chair and one other Member also met with the Government Minister soon after the Educating Engineers report to hear about progress made with policy on how engineering education might be provided.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 26.03pt; padding-left:2.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee has not yet taken up the option to seek training from outside professionals.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Appendix 1 – Awayday Recommendations</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Core objectives, wider relationships and impact </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee be more explicit in highlighting differences between Westminster and the devolved nations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee consider what outputs it might produce beyond a report to enhance awareness of its work and inquiries</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee should consider a long detailed look at the Research Councils and whether they properly fulfil the role they were designed for.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#af6227; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Committee strategy</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee spend more time on planning and strategy in private meetings on Mondays (regularly but not weekly)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Committee specialists provide regular updates to the Committee about their meetings with external stakeholders, in order to inform planning for potential inquiries</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee could consider conducting more follow-ups to previous inquiries.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Private business, committee papers and staff support</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One or two Mondays a month be set aside for private business considerations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee staff should investigate ways to ensure Members receive their papers in a timely fashion (greater effort to ensure regular Thursday circulation).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Committee staff should investigate how the format of papers might better facilitate the use of files on the share drive.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#af6227; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Preparing and approving Committee reports</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee allow more time at the end of oral evidence sessions to accommodate regular discussion about the direction of the inquiry and potential recommendations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee, where appropriate, be given two weekends to consider and table amendments to reports longer than 20 pages</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee staff should consider the use of track changes in Word as a way of making it easier to follow amendments.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Public meetings</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee might meet some witnesses (e.g. academics) in private before evidence sessions to put them at ease</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the leaflet available to the public gallery for each evidence session could include a short feedback form</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Forward programme – scoping new inquiries</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#af6227; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee focus more on its oversight function</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee consider how to best scrutinise the way in which public money is spent on science, for example, by commissioning studies from the National Audit Office to help inform future inquiries</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That the Committee consider arranging an informal meeting with representatives from the scientific community to help inform its forward programme. This could be in the format of a poster session with invitations being extended to other relevant select committees</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Future inquiries on marine science and decline in the honeybee population should be fully scoped for immediate consideration. Discussion on others should be delayed until the next Monday afternoon planning meeting.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#af6227; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Press/media issues</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Media team involved much earlier in the writing process, before finalising Chair’s draft</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members to actively engage with local media when appropriate</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#af6227; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Committee website and use of social media</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Significant changes to the format of the website to make it more interactive, multi-media and user friendly</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Members will participate in providing media clips to achieve this end</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Appendix 2 – Liaison Committee Recommendations </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">1. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">Our Committee has asked the Procedure Committee to consider whether members wishing to leave a committee could be counted as discharged, even if it means that the lack of an applicant leaves a vacancy on the committee. We reiterate the concern we expressed in the last Parliament about the size of select committees and support the Wright Committee's recommendation that the size of departmental committees should not normally be more than 11 members. (Paragraph 29)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We encourage other committees to make use of the support of the Scrutiny Unit and to discuss with the National Audit Office how its programme of work might help support the work of the committee. (Paragraph 42)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">As a model of "best practice", we recommend that committees:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a candid discussion amongst themselves about how they see their purpose, and what they wish to achieve over the length of the Parliament;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identify what are the most important functions of their department's responsibilities and design a programme of scrutiny to assess whether the department's objectives have been fulfilled;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clearly record their conclusions and remind themselves of them when considering proposals for inquiry and programme planning;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">review this at least annually, with an "</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">awayday</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">" or at least a longer, less formal discussion than is possible at a regular deliberative meeting; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">canvass opinion among the key players in their subject area about their performance. (Paragraph 65)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">4.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We expect Government departments to be transparent about their objectives, and we ought to practise what we preach. We commend to other committees the practice of publishing strategic objectives, and of consulting their department and other stakeholders on them. (Paragraph 66)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that, before they launch an inquiry, committees agree a comprehensive minute setting out what they hope to achieve, and the likelihood of success. (Paragraph 69)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">6.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that in future inquiries, as a matter of routine, committees include consideration of the financial aspects and implications of the policies being examined. This could include for instance, what the justification for spending public money is, what evidence there is that it will offer, or is offering, good value for money to the taxpayer, what alternatives have been considered and whether they would be likely to be more effective, and the outcomes expected to be added to or improved upon by the spending. (Paragraph 72)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">7.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We encourage committees to hold evidence sessions at least annually with ministers and departmental accounting officers, and include within these sessions consideration of how departments evaluate and take decisions on spending, and how they assess the effectiveness of the spending they undertake. (Paragraph 73)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">8.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We encourage committees to review departments' Mid-Year Reports when published, using them to identify relevant issues and questions relating to finance and performance. (Paragraph 74)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">9.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that committees experiment with different approaches, such as appointing a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">rapporteur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none"> to lead on a particular inquiry, or choosing "lead questioners" for an evidence session. (Paragraph 76)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">10.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that committees make every effort to broaden their range of witnesses, and to take into account the principles of diversity and inclusion in planning their inquiries and committee programme. (Paragraph 77)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">11.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">Committees should bear in mind the option of commissioning research when planning their long-term strategies, and, if necessary, the House authorities should increase the money available for this purpose. (Paragraph 78)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">12.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We encourage committees to keep their reports short and accessible, and to avoid too many recommendations. A clear indication of which recommendations are most important will help the committee achieve impact and make follow-up easier. We recommend that the usual template for committee reports be changed to distinguish clearly the recommendations targeted at the Government. We suggest that conclusions should be in bold, with recommendations in bold italics, and that it should be clearly stated to whom the recommendation is addressed. (Paragraph 79)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">13.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that each committee should appoint a member of staff, or an adviser, or an outside body, who will monitor follow-up to recommendations in respect of each report. The committee should report to the House at least once in each parliamentary Session upon how many of its recommendations the Government has acted, and what follow-up is proposed on outstanding recommendations. (Paragraph 83)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">14.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">It is sensible for departmental select committees to be able to cross departmental boundaries when this is in the interest of effective scrutiny of matters which go beyond a single department, but they should do so in ways which respect the role of other departmental select committees and in full consultation with the chairs of those committees. (Paragraph 84)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">15.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that the introductory briefings offered to new committee members be given more formality, and include a meeting with the chair or another experienced committee member. When there is significant turnover following a reshuffle, for example, a programme of collective briefings for new committee members should be arranged. (Paragraph 96)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">16.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that committees consider the benefits of using professional trainers to help them refresh and develop their questioning skills. (Paragraph 97)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">17.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-transform:none">We recommend that chairs discuss with their committee how they see their role, and seek their endorsement for it. At this stage in the Parliament, there may be benefit in chairs asking their committees for individual feedback on their chairmanship, as an aid to the chair's professional development and to encourage committee engagement. (Paragraph 100) </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">9 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>